Source:  Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  13
Edition:
Quote:  Bullocks were also driven in sledges (two or four bullocks). The iron iron which passed under the bullocks' necks to keep the yoke in place was called the<i> bow</i>. The <i>bow</i> was held to the yoke by a <i>yoke key</i> which passed through a hole in it. (C. [Butler A First Year in Canterbury Settlement], p.95, etc.)
Notes:  Acland Glossary

